flavor.explanation.vspread: Acts exactly like the regular 'spread' function, but inserts a one tick delay between each vertical layer of the spread. Always uses its current position as the initial y value instead of the center; intended to reduce lag for larger structures.
gamerule.portalFrequency.description: Change the frequency of Portal Ruins. Defaults to 50%.
flavor.explanation.pillar: Generates a pillar going downwards, with up to two randomly selected main blocks, and up to two randomly selected 'break' blocks placed at set intervals. $m[block]m$ and $mf[block]mf$ determine the main and main flavor blocks; $s[block]s$ and $sf[block]sf$ determine the break and break flavor blocks; $mc[float]mc$ and $sc[float]sc$ determine the chance of using a flavor block instead of the standard block. $w[integer]w$ determines the width, $rd[integer]rd$ sets an optional required distance, and $b[integer]b$ determines the distance between 'break' layers.

flavor.explanation.map: Checks for any blue wool in one block below and up to seven blocks away from the centerpoint; and converts it into different wool colors, maping out the surrounding area. The color of each block is determined by the biome at that block's offset from the center, multiplied by 100.

flavor.explanation.depopulate: Just despawns stuff in order to prevent Mindthemood's Marvelous Modpack from marvelously crashing your server. Unlike the kill command, it can be given a random chance of despawning target entities, ($mc[float]mc$). It also requires a target entity type, $m[entity]m$, and range. $s[integer]s$. Recommended to use with a higher delay than other flavor blocks.

flavor.explanation.explode: Creates a simulated-explosion effect. $s[integer]s$ determines the size of the explosion, $d[integer]d$ determines the destructiveness, $c[float]c$ determines the likelihood the explosion occurs, (1 by default), $g[float]g$ determines the likelihood of converting stone/sand based blocks into sand/gravel instead of destroying them, and $sc[float]sc$ determines the likelihood of scattering a block instead of destroying it. Note that the actual explosion may spread up to 10% larger than the provided size.

flavor.explanation.update: Simply updates the block directly below the flavor block. (Destroys and replaces it), allowing naturally ticking blocks to tick correctly when loaded from a pregenerated structure. Primarily used to trigger legacy genblocks, that is, to allow Mindthemoods to avoid properly fixing old junk.
flavor.explanation.paint: Summons a painting on a wall the block is connected to, with the block serving as the bottom left hand corner. $variant[string]variant$ specifies a specific painting, and $s[string]s$ specifies a size; it can be set to small, landscape, portrait, medium, vista, large, or giant. Defaults to small if no size is selected.

flavor.explanation.stair: The stair command generates a 1m-wide staircase in the direction the block is facing, directly in front of and 1 block below itself. $m[block]m$ specifies the main block to use, $s[block]s$ specifies a block to use for the stairs, $t[block]t$ specifies a tertiary flavor block for the main block, and $sf[block]sf$ specifies an alternate stair block. $inverted$ generates a single block support rather than a vertical platform, and $required$ generates the stairwell even if there isn't a solid stopping point within a reasonable distance. ($md[integer]md$ determines the horizontal distance from the starting point that the stair is allowed to search for a stopping position.)
flavor.explanation.spread: The spread command targets every block in a box centered on the Flavor Block, spreading ruined variants. $x[integer]x$, $y[integer]y$, and $z[integer]z$ determine the distance from the center to the corners of the affected area; $i[float]i$ determines the likelihood of an individual block being effected, and $c[]c$ determines carry, the chance that each adjacent block is ruined. $w[float]w$ determines the chance of placing type-specific features, $d[float]d$ determines the chance of destroying partial ruinable blocks, and $db[blockstate]db$ the block to replace them with. $a[float]a$, if present, determines the chance of placing suspicious blocks. $filler$ will add loot to pottery and chiseled bookshelves, $vines$ will spread vines, $lichen$ spreads lichen, $bonemeal$ spreads and variates plants, $snowy$ does snow cover, and $inset$ adds custom chiseled blocks if Charming chisels is installed. Lastly, $type[string]type$ Enables certain unique properties. mossy, frozen, spider, forest, coral, village, trail, lush, dune, fortress, bastion, ancient, monument, and city are all valid.

flavor.explanation.populate: The populate command summons entities, with optional randomization. $m[entity_id]m$ sets the main entity, $s[entity_id]s$ sets a secondary entity, and $t[entity_id]t$ sets a tertiary entity. $mc[float]mc$, $sc[float]sc$, and $tc[float]tc$ determine the chances of a successful summoning. $persistent$ sets all summoned entities to have persistence enabled, $r[integer]r$ repeats the function, and $o[integer]o$ sets a maxiumum offset from the source block.
